# Testing Results

## 4. Surveys
To design an effective pre- and post-interaction questionnaire, we must focus on psychometric consistency. 
By using a Likert scale (typically 1–5 or 1–7), we can quantify subjective feelings like "stress" and "confidence" into actionable data points.

As a user researcher, I recommend administering 
• Objective: Quantify how much the system demystifies the marketing process by measuring Confidence Scores.
• Format: Distribute to 10+ participants these 5 questions twice: once immediately before onboarding (to capture the baseline) and once after the user completes their first Recipe task (to measure the "lift"), shared on TechLabs Slack. 
• Success Indicator: A targeted 80% of users should report feeling "Less Anxious" after completing their first 7-day recipe.
• Survey Items (1–5 Likert Scale):
    * Clarity of Direction: "I feel certain about exactly which marketing task/s I should prioritize right now to reach my business or professional goals." Goal: Measures the effectiveness of the Recipe Book in reducing decision paralysis.
    * Creative Friction: "I find it easy to translate core features or activities into engaging messages for different social platforms." Goal: Measures the "Blank Page" pain point and the perceived value of the Content Engine.
    * Emotional State (Stress Management): "I feel calm and in control when I think about my upcoming marketing requirements or activities." Goal: Quantifies the stress levels associated with the "Pre-Launch Panic."
    * Time Competency: "I am confident that I can produce professional-quality marketing materials in under 30 minutes."Goal: Measures the perception of efficiency and the "GPS" vision of the product.
    * Outcome Agency: "I believe my current marketing actions will directly result in measurable growth for my business or professional growth." Goal: Measures "Sarah's" ROI anxiety and "Alex's" need for a repeatable process.
